Analysis of COVID-19 Deaths in the United States

Anirud Kashyap

The purpose of this tutorial is to demonstrate the data science pipeline in full. In order to do so, the data utilizes COVID-19 data. COVID-19 was a global pandemic that wreaked havoc through much of the world during 2019-2022, killing millions of people and resulting in some serious, long-lasting complications for many (known as long COVID). There was a plethora of factors that resulted in all of these tragedies (not just the virus itself), including but not limited to misinformation, politics, etc.

Why are all of these things important? Given the amount of data related to COVID-19, detailed analysis and examination of all of the datasets allow data scientists and other researchers to determine the main causes and hopefully use that, along with other research, to prevent another pandemic that may attempt to wreak havoc on planet earth in the near future.

In this tutorial, we will go through the entire data science lifecycle.

Part 1: Data Collection

The first step in the data science pipline is collecting data that is related to the topic this tutorial is focusing on: analyzing COVID-19 deaths and how other various factors such as age group and pre-existing medical conditions may have contributed. Given the significant amount of misinformation that was taking place during this time period, it's important to always consider the validity of data, especially when it involves health.

The dataset using during this tutorial was obtained through this source. Fortunately, upon examination of the individual datasets within the repository, the data were obtained from the respective country's governmental organization that was collecting the COVID-related data as seen here.

All of the individual datasets were stored in the convienent form of a comma-separated value file.

Part 2: Data Processing

The purpose of this tutorial is to analyze COVID-19 deaths that have taken place on the global scale. The datasets obtained the first part of the data science pipeline contain many useful features and are formatted in a certain way. However, some of these features add no value, and the way the dataset is set up will hinder our ability to analyze the large datasets.

In this part, we will process the data by cleaning it up, reorganizing it, and using an imputation technique mentioned later below so that we are able to carry out the remaining stages of the data science pipeline.

Our end goal is to have one dataframe with all of the respective features combined and no missing data.

Let's go ahead and define some helper functions that will be useful in this step of the pipeline.

This helper function takes in a dataframe (df) and a list of features (columns of the dataframe) that are considered unnecessary and need to be removed.

In[]:
def remove_unnecessary_features(df, features):
    # Drops the features along axis=1
    return df.drop(features, axis=1)

This helper function removes observations in a dataframe that contain a value in a particular feature that will not be used in our data analysis.

In[]:
def remove_unnecessary_observations(df, feature_name, feature_values):
    
    # Removes all feature_values from the feature feature_name
    df = df[~df[feature_name].isin(feature_values)]

    # Returns the newly filtered dataframe
    return df

This helper function performs a mean imputation technique by filling in the missing np.nan observations with the mean value.

In[]:
def perform_mean_imp(df, feature_name):
    df[feature_name].fillna(df[feature_name].mean(), inplace=True)

This helper function checks to see if the dataframe df has any missing values in the feathre feature_name.

In[]:
def missing_values_present(df, feature_name):
    return df[feature_name].isnull().values.any()

Part 3: Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization

Now that we have a version of our dataset that has been cleaned, filtered, and processed, we are ready to proceed to the next stage of the data science of exploring and visualizing our dataset.

We are interested in analysing the COVID-19 deaths that depend on various factors such as vaccinations, hospilizations, etc. Let's try to see some trends between the COVID-19 deaths all of our relevant features including but not limited to boosters, vaccinations, hospitalizations, etc. in our dataset.

Let's first see how the COVID-19 deaths have trended over time in all of the countries and make any possible conjectures based on the visualization.

# Makes the graph more readable
months = [calendar.month_name[i] for i in range(1,13)]

# Helper function that graphs the COVID-19 deaths data
# in the dataframe df for a given year
def graph_plot(df, year, title, ylabel):
    
    df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

    df_filt = df[df['date'].dt.year == year[0]]

    # Computes the sum of COVID-19 deaths for a given month
    data_one = df_filt.groupby(df_filt['date'].dt.month)['value'].sum()

    # Handles case where graph for the January of next year
    # shows up in the plot
    if len(data_one) != 12:    
        data_one = data_one.reindex(range(1, 13),fill_value=0)

    # Plots the data for the first year
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    data_one.plot(kind='bar')
    
    # Makes the x axis more readable by using the months
    # that was formatted thanks to the calendar library
    plt.xticks(range(12), months, rotation=45) 
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title[0])

    ##########################################
    # Code below is a repeat of the code above
    ##########################################
    df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

    df_filt = df[df['date'].dt.year == year[1]]

    data_one = df_filt.groupby(df_filt['date'].dt.month)['value'].sum()

    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    data_one.plot(kind='bar')
    
    plt.xticks(range(12), months, rotation=45) 
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title[1])

It's important to observe we are just noting some of the observations of these plots and NOT making any conjectures.

Now let's see how the COVID-19 hospitalizations relate to these trends.

In[]:
# Helper function that graphs the hospitalizations rate data
# that's in the dataframe df for the year.
def graph_hospitalizations(df, year, title, color):

    # Filters out the dataframe so that we only have the Daily ICU occupancy rate and observations
    # that were collected during the year
    df_new = df[(df['indicator'] == 'Daily ICU occupancy') & (df['date'].str.startswith(year))]

    df_new['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_new['date'])

    # Sorts the dataframe by the date for processing
    df_new = df_new.sort_values(by='date')

    # Plots the data
    plt.plot(df_new['date'], df_new['value'], marker='o', color=color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Daily ICU Occupancy')
    plt.title(title)

As we can see in the above plots, during 2020 we see that the daily ICU occupancy increased sharply in March (which was when it was declared as a pandemic by the WHO), but surprisingly dipped but then continued to increase at a rapid rate. In 2021, we see there was a sharp decline but a sudden rise towards the Fall of 2021. We can see a inverse trend with the COVID-19 vaccinations during this year. As the number of COVID-19 vaccinations being administered was increasing, the daily ICU occupancy admittance was decreasing.

Furthermore, we can see that in 2022 and 2023, the number of daily admittance to the ICU had decreased significantly (25000-> ~5000), which was during the period where the amount of COVID-19 vaccinations being administered remained roughly stagnant. It should also be noted that the number of deaths was flucuating as seen earlier in this tutorial.

It's important to observe we are just noting some of the observations of these plots and NOT making any conjectures.

Let's see how the reproduction rate relates to these trends.

In[]:
# Helper function that graphs the reproduction rate data
# in the dataframe df for the year
def graph_rr(df, year, title, color):

    # Filters out the dataframe so that only the observations
    # collected during year are there
    df = df[df['date'].str.startswith(year)]
    df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

    # Sorts the dataframe by the date for proessing
    df = df.sort_values(by='date')

    # Plots the reproduction rate
    plt.plot(df['date'], df['reproduction_rate'], color=color)
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('COVID-19 Reproduction Rate')
    plt.title(title)

In[]:
nn = keras.Sequential()
custom_optimizer = keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.01) 

# Input layer
nn.add(Dense(units=64, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],)))

# Hidden Layers
nn.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=32, activation='relu'))
nn.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=16, activation='relu'))

# The final output neuron
nn.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=1, activation='sigmoid'))

nn.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

Our neural network above consists of the input layer (which essentially is a feature vector), followed by three hidden layers of 64, 32, and 16 units -- all of which using the ReLu activation function, respectively. Our last "layer" is the output layer, which utilizes the sigmoid activation function to ensure the output falls in the range of [0,1].

The above regular neural network utilizes the stochastic gradient descent optimization algorithm, which optimizes the weights.

Now that we have designed our neural network, let's go ahead and train it.

Evaluating performance of the Neural Network

Let's go ahead perform some validation tests to see how well our neural network model is able to predict the COVID-19 deaths based on the features mentioned at the beginning of this step of the data science pipeline.

We will utilize the result provided by the Tensorflow Keras library (which we will use as a baseline). We will also utilize 10-fold cross validation.

In[]:
loss, accuracy = nn.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
print('Accuracy of the Neural Network is %.2f%%' % (accuracy * 100))

3/3  0s 1ms/step - accuracy: 0.0182 - loss: 0.1643 
Accuracy of the Neural Network is 1.30%

That will serve as our baseline accuracy. Let's go ahead and now perform 5-fold cross validation.

Let's go ahead and set up the algorithm, utilizing the Kfold library from sklearn. It's important to note that this will involve training our Neural Network again.

Given the size of this dataset, it's important to note that this step may take a while given some of the computation constraints of the machine this tutorial was created on.

In[]:
folds = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True)
X =  master_df_norm[['total_vaccinations', 'hospitalizations', 'reproduction_rate']].values
y = master_df_norm[['deaths']].values
prev_accuracy = []
for train_index, val_index in folds.split(X,y):
    
    X_train, X_val = X[train_index], X[val_index]
    y_train, y_val = y[train_index], y[val_index]

    # Trains our Neural Network from above
    prev_results = nn.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=20, batch_size=32, validation_data=(X_val, y_val), verbose=0)

    loss, accuracy = nn.evaluate(X_val, y_val, verbose=1)
    prev_accuracy.append(accuracy)

In[]:
for i in range(len(prev_accuracy)):
    print(f'Accuracy of the {i}th fold: ', prev_accuracy[i])

Accuracy of the 0th fold:  0.019607843831181526
Accuracy of the 1th fold:  0.03921568766236305
Accuracy of the 2th fold:  0.019607843831181526
Accuracy of the 3th fold:  0.0784313753247261
Accuracy of the 4th fold:  0.03999999910593033
Average accuracy: 3.94%

As we can see above, our average accuracy of 3.94% is higher than the accuracy without the cross validation, though our overall accuracy rate is relatively low than what was expected. This can be the result of some overfitting issues that were created during the training of our neural networks.

As discussed in the documentation provided at the beginning of this stage, the training portion consists of forward propagation as well as back propagation, updating the values of the weights, to which they can become smaller or bigger. If the weights become too large, this can result in overfitting issues, where the Neural Network learns all of the noise associated with the data.

Furthermore, given the amount of missing data this dataset consisted of, it's quite possible that this resulted in an unfavorable accuracy rate.

Part 5: Insight & Policy Decision

This portion represents the final stage in the datascience pipeline, where we are safe to draw some valid conclusions regarding our dataset.

  1. Based on the given data, as the reproduction rate of the COVID-19 virus increases, the number of deaths also increases

  2. There is no clear relationship between the number of hospitalizations and the corresponding COVID-19 deaths.

In conclusion, we are able to use the data and all of the analysis performed above to see how we are able to contain not just COVID-19 (though at the time of creating this tutorial, COVID-19 is virtually nonexistent) but also other viruses that can result in a global pandemic on a scale seen with COVID-19. We can use this data and analysis to prevent the tragedies of millions of people.

The purpose of this tutorial was to illustrate some of the key components of the data science pipeline. Each step within the data science pipeline consists of many small steps. In other words, we have access to many tools but we choose to "build the house" with the tools that feel are necessary.

I hope that you were able to see how we were able to make the meaningful conclusions and how we can leverage the data in our favor.

This tutorial illustrated the data science pipeline in full: Data Collection -> Data Processing -> Exploratory Data Analysis & Visualation -> Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, & ML -> Insight.
